    <sem:object xml:lang="eng" datatype="xsd:string">Fourteen books in the New Testament that were originally letters written by the Apostle Paul to members of the Church. They may be divided into groups as follows:Paul wrote the epistles to the Thessalonians from Corinth during his second missionary journey. His work in Thessalonica is described in . He wanted to return to Thessalonica, but he was unable to do so (). He therefore sent Timothy to cheer the converts and bring him word about how they were doing. The first epistle is the outcome of his thankfulness on Timothyâ€™s return. The second epistle was written a short time later.Paul wrote the epistles to the Corinthians during his third missionary journey to answer questions and correct disorder among the Saints in Corinth.Paul wrote these epistles while he was in prison the first time in Rome.Paul wrote these epistles after he was released from prison in Rome the first time.</sem:object>
